issue.body:
Hi,

It is possible to create a server config for domains with multiple wildcards, like `*.*.current.test`

Everything will work, and the TLS certificate will be created correctly (if using tls internal). 

However the generated certificate will be for exactly this domain — and the browsers normally don’t accept certificates with multiple wildcards. 

Would it be possible to generate / request the certificate only with one wildcard and a fixed subdomain on-the-fly?

like sub2.sub.current.test will with server config `*.*.current.test` should then request a certificate for `*.sub.current.test`. 

This way we could still get a compatible certificate. 


Appreciate your thoughts
Thanks

comment.body:
@mholt sorry, the formatting got messed up as the `*` was replaced to something markdown. I wrote this issue on my phone, just fixed the formatting on my computer.

@francislavoie just to be clear:

Caddy (or the ACME server inside it which is used when using `tls internal` is already generating certificates with two wildcards.

This config:

```caddy
*.*.current.test {
	tls internal
	# ...
}
```

will generate a certificate with SAN `*.*.current.test`:

![CleanShot 2022-12-08 at 10 10 12](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1032411/206405744-6034cb44-23b8-4cbf-a362-0a3b9075ebca.png)

That is the behaviour in Caddy today in version `v2.6.2 h1:wKoFIxpmOJLGl3QXoo6PNbYvGW4xLEgo32GPBEjWL8o=`.


What I am asking for is if there is a compromise between this valid config with `*.*.current.test` and the invalid certificate with SAN `*.*.current.test`.

One way to do it would be to resolve the host at runtime and request a certificate with a specific subdomain and only the wildcard on level 4.

I hope this clears things up.

Sorry for the confusion about the bad message formatting in Github.

issue.body:
Hi,

It is possible to create a server config for domains with multiple wildcards, like `*.*.current.test`

Everything will work, and the TLS certificate will be created correctly (if using tls internal). 

However the generated certificate will be for exactly this domain — and the browsers normally don’t accept certificates with multiple wildcards. 

Would it be possible to generate / request the certificate only with one wildcard and a fixed subdomain on-the-fly?

like sub2.sub.current.test will with server config `*.*.current.test` should then request a certificate for `*.sub.current.test`. 

This way we could still get a compatible certificate. 


Appreciate your thoughts
Thanks

comment.body:
@mholt sorry, the formatting got messed up as the `*` was replaced to something markdown. I wrote this issue on my phone, just fixed the formatting on my computer.

@francislavoie just to be clear:

Caddy (or the ACME server inside it which is used when using `tls internal` is already generating certificates with two wildcards.

This config:

```caddy
*.*.current.test {
	tls internal
	# ...
}
```

will generate a certificate with SAN `*.*.current.test`:

![CleanShot 2022-12-08 at 10 10 12](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1032411/206405744-6034cb44-23b8-4cbf-a362-0a3b9075ebca.png)

That is the behaviour in Caddy today in version `v2.6.2 h1:wKoFIxpmOJLGl3QXoo6PNbYvGW4xLEgo32GPBEjWL8o=`.


What I am asking for is if there is a compromise between this valid config with `*.*.current.test` and the invalid certificate with SAN `*.*.current.test`.

One way to do it would be to resolve the host at runtime and request a certificate with a specific subdomain and only the wildcard on level 4.

I hope this clears things up.

Sorry for the confusion about the bad message formatting in Github.

![CleanShot 2022-12-08 at 10 10 12](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1032411/206405744-6034cb44-23b8-4cbf-a362-0a3b9075ebca.png)

That is the behaviour in Caddy today in version `v2.6.2 h1:wKoFIxpmOJLGl3QXoo6PNbYvGW4xLEgo32GPBEjWL8o=`.


What I am asking for is if there is a compromise between this valid config with `*.*.current.test` and the invalid certificate with SAN `*.*.current.test`.

One way to do it would be to resolve the host at runtime and request a certificate with a specific subdomain and only the wildcard on level 4.

I hope this clears things up.

Sorry for the confusion about the bad message formatting in Github.

issue.title: Smarter multi-wildcard certificates
issue.body:
Hi,

It is possible to create a server config for domains with multiple wildcards, like *.*.current.tes

Everything will work, and the TLS certificate will be created correctly (if using tls internal). 

However the generated certificate will be for exactly this domain — and the browsers normally don’t accept certificates with multiple wildcards. 

Would it be possible to generate / request the certificate only with one wildcard and a fixed subdomain on-the-fly?

like sub2.sub.current.test will with server config *.*.current.test should then request a certificate for *.sub.current.test. 

This way we could still get a compatible certificate. 


Appreciate your thoughts
Thanks
